    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Roofs: Overview
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Understanding Walkables, Roof Tiles, Cell Altitudes, and PAP Flags.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What is the Roofs Tab?
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Roofs tab</Bold> provides functionality for managing four interconnected systems
        that control vertical space and surfaces in Urban Chaos:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Walkables</Bold> — Containers attached to buildings that hold Roof Face 4 tiles
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Roof Face 4 (RF4) tiles</Bold> — Individual roof/floor surface tiles that live
                inside walkables
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Cell Altitudes</Bold> — Vertical offset of each map cell (measured in quarter storeys)
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>PAP Flags</Bold> — Properties that tell the engine how each cell should behave
                (hidden, water, no-go, etc.)
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/roofs_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: Roofs tab showing Walkables list, RF4 tiles list, Cell Altitude controls, and PAP Flags panel
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,16,0,4">
        Automatic vs Manual Management
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        In most cases, <Bold>you don't need to manually manage roofs</Bold>. The Auto-Build system
        (enabled in the Buildings tab) automatically handles walkables, roof tiles, cell altitudes,
        and PAP flags when you create closed polygon structures.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        When Auto-Build Handles Everything
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        When you draw walls that form a closed polygon, the Auto-Build system automatically:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Creates a <Bold>walkable container</Bold> at the appropriate height
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                For <Bold>warehouses</Bold>: Fills the walkable with <Bold>RF4 tiles</Bold> matching
                the interior footprint
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                For <Bold>houses</Bold>: Sets the <Bold>cell altitude</Bold> to represent roof height
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Sets appropriate <Bold>PAP flags</Bold> (RoofExists for houses, Hidden for warehouses)
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        When to Use Manual Management
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        You'll need to use the Roofs tab manually for:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Sloped roofs</Bold> — Adjusting individual RF4 tile corner heights to create
                pitched or angled roofs
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Elevated structures</Bold> — Creating bridges, platforms, or raised areas without
                closed polygonal facets
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Overlapping walkables</Bold> — Adding multiple walkable regions at different
                heights on the same building
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Special surface properties</Bold> — Marking cells as water, no-go zones, or
                mission event areas
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Fine-tuning</Bold> — Adjusting heights or flags that the Auto-Build system didn't
                set exactly as desired
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Understanding the Four Systems
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        1. Walkables (Containers)
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Walkables</Bold> are rectangular containers attached to buildings. They define a
        bounding box (X1, Z1 to X2, Z2) and a height. Walkables do <Bold>not</Bold> define surfaces
        themselves — they are simply organizational containers that hold Roof Face 4 tiles.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Each walkable stores:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Building ID</Bold> — Which building owns this walkable
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Bounding box</Bold> — X1, Z1, X2, Z2 coordinates
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Height</Bold> — Vertical position in quarter storeys
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>RF4 range</Bold> — Start and end indices pointing to the RF4 tiles it contains
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        2. Roof Face 4 Tiles (RF4)
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Roof Face 4 tiles</Bold> (also called RF4 or roof tiles) are the actual walkable surfaces.
        Each RF4 tile defines a 1×1 cell surface with four corner heights, allowing for sloped or
        angled roofs.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Each RF4 tile stores:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Position</Bold> — X and Z coordinates (absolute, not relative to walkable)
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>SE corner height</Bold> — Base height of the cell in quarter storeys
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>NW, NE, SW corner offsets</Bold> — Height deltas in pixels (for slopes)
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Roof direction</Bold> — Which way the tile splits diagonally
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Special marker</Bold> — Usually set for roof tiles (exact purpose unclear)
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        RF4 tiles are used in <Bold>warehouse buildings</Bold> (for floors) and <Bold>houses with
        sloped roofs</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        3. Cell Altitudes
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Cell altitude</Bold> controls the vertical offset of each map cell. This is <Bold>not</Bold>
        the terrain height (which is controlled by the Heights tab) — it's a separate layer that
        defines roof surfaces for non-warehouse buildings.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Cell altitude is measured in <Bold>quarter storeys</Bold> and is typically set automatically
        when houses are built. For warehouses, cell altitude stays at 0 because RF4 tiles define
        the interior floor height instead.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        You can manually set cell altitudes to create elevated areas like bridges or platforms
        without needing closed polygonal facets.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        4. PAP Flags
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>PAP flags</Bold> are binary properties attached to each cell that tell the engine
        how the cell should behave. Multiple flags can be set on a single cell.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Common flags include:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>RoofExists</Bold> — Player should stand on the roof altitude (non-warehouses)
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Hidden</Bold> — Cell is an interior cell with a ceiling above it (warehouses)
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>NoGo</Bold> — Player cannot enter this cell (functions like No Go Zone in missions)
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Water</Bold> — Marks the tile as water (sets sink behavior)
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Zone flags</Bold> — Can be used for mission event trigger areas
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        See <Bold>Roofs: PAP Flags</Bold> for a complete list and detailed descriptions.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Building Filter Integration
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Roofs tab is tightly integrated with the Buildings tab. When you select a building
        in the Buildings tab, that building is <Bold>automatically passed through</Bold> to the
        Roofs tab building filter.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        This means:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                When you select Building #5 in Buildings tab, the Roofs tab automatically filters
                to show only walkables attached to Building #5
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                You can manually change the filter by selecting a different building from the
                dropdown in the Roofs tab
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                You can clear the filter to see <Bold>all</Bold> walkables from all buildings
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

